<br>
The statement had been delivered in the same tone that he had always used, the Georgia accent untainted by emotion or stress. Even ten years after being released from her sire’s hunting glances, she remembered. <br>
<br>
She could recall his neatly trimmed beard and mustache, red flecked with gray. The formal dress shirt, always worn with cufflinks, the dove gray tailored jacket. Standing with his hands clasped informally behind his back, his every glance and movement betraying his contempt of those around him.<br>
<br>
Even after ten years. She remembered and felt the heat rise on her cheeks.<br>
<br>
“The large majority seems to think my place is with a stake between my ribs.”<br>
<br>
“You only have yourself to blame for that, Justice.”<br>
<br>
A pity, that a vampire cannot cry.<br>
<br>
“If this clan-mate was really a vile as you claim, it should not have been at all difficult to get permission of the sixth on him. Then, he would still be disposed of. And you wouldn’t be running.”<br>
<br>
The utter determination rose in her gut. “I’m not running.” Her voice breathy over the public telephone as she swallowed her tears. “I’m relocating.”<br>
<br>
“Really?” His voice was slow, and Justice could just picture a half-smirk on his infuriating face, an eyebrow going up. “I’d like to know just what sort of place you expect to relocate to, now that a city, so controversial among the Camarillia that it might as well be Anarch, has kicked you out.”<br>
<br>
“They didn’t kick me out.” Justice gave a short smile of minimal satisfaction at this, more like a baring of teeth against the encroaching darkness. “A friend told me it might be a good idea for me to leave.” The unfamiliar word started the thoughts circling in her head, though. Someone had betrayed her to Nikka. Who did she know that was really a friend anymore? Thomas, Calith, Ali, Laura? Were there any she could trust?<br>
<br>
The memory came to her with startling clarity for about two seconds: an old Ventrue acquaintance of hers. ‘Friends—better to buy too many and be left busy than to buy too little and be left dead.’<br>
<br>
Was Calith dead? No way to tell, now. And what about little Marissa? Could Thomas protect her from whatever Brujah was elevated to primogen in her place?<br>
<br>
“Then it’s sheer folly to return.” For how old he sounded, the man ought to be a lot closer to Caine. Could you raise the potency of your blood by sheer arrogance? Justice had full conviction in the idea that if such a thing could be done, her sire would have done it by now.<br>
<br>
“I know.”<br>
<br>
“Which means you’re going to go it anyway.”<br>
<br>
“It doesn’t concern you.” A silence entered the conversation, of medium length.<br>
<br>
“No, you’re right. It doesn’t.”<br>
<br>
Justice had a distinct feeling of foreboding, that Kevin McGovern Jr., her esteemed sire and a respected professor at the University of California Berkeley, was either about to disinherit her or hang up the phone. Or both. But then he began to speak again.<br>
<br>
“It doesn’t. But if you’re going to get yourself killed, do us all a favor and stay out of the Bay Area when you do it.” And then he hung up.<br>
<br>
Justice sighed as she hung up the receiver and climbed back on her motorcycle. She touched her forehead to the cool metal of the handlebars for just a minute, trying to let the tension flow out of her neck and shoulders. She wasn’t sure if she had served any purpose at all by calling Kevin and telling him of her plight. Perhaps at most it had given her an impetus to action.<br>
<br>
She found the nearest highway entrance around the outskirts of Watsonville, and started heading the general direction of South. All the bad little vampires ran south, always, when they were booted. And in any case, if she were truly courting death, as Mr. McGovern seemed eager to believe, she wanted to see the Joshua trees of the desert before she died.<br>
<br>
Really, she ought to call him again and leave a message of thanks on the old bastard’s answering machine. There was nothing like a little iron-clad practicality to shred good-hearted rebellion and idealism into far-flung bloody chunks.<br>
