<br>
It’s bare, stark, naked almost in the postmodern sense. In the middle of the night one can almost imagine that it is the asphalt carpet the four horsemen will ride: that it is a tribute to the ultimate chaos. Not anarchy or dissolution or fundamental dissonance, but…nothing. Simply that, nothing. The absence of all that is vibrancy and life.<br>
<br>
It leaves ample space for dark thoughts.<br>
<br>
Juanita: the way her hair, long and thick and curly and always touched with dew from the fog, would smother you when she came close, would grasp you and hold you tight with the smell of rain and stars. Her body, perfect elegance—controlled power in the movement of every muscle. Her lips, black cherries, and as intoxicating as a good Merlot. She was the kind of woman that could make you remember what love was like, embodied it as the simplest sweetness that came before the heady onrush of something darker.<br>
<br>
My Fire Girl, my baby. The images were coming back to her on this darkly oppressive highway, suddenly, like the flashes of the pig’s lights on weathered brick had. Stark moments of color, of panic, of sweat and emotion that rose like a forest fire and painted the blood acrid. The feelings were ancient: sex and adrenaline, passion and pain. It reappeared in a rush, unfolded itself from the back of her mind, the first time she had seen the chola. Dark-eyed women not-huddling in the alleyway, women that were still little girls’ deep inside.<br>
<br>
The relationship had been deceptively simple to establish. Justice had connected them to customers from CSU Los Angeles that might want the smack they peddled and kept the eyes of the local pigs turned nicely away. In return, Justice was on-hand as the gang began to make more money, moving from smack to crack to angel dust. They began to get what little notoriety they could hold onto in the dog eat puppy world they had chosen. Predictably, none of the girls actually saved the money—it went into 40’s and guns and lazy vatos that promised, someday, they would take care of the Girls and of course never did.<br>
<br>
Only Juanita had wanted more. They used to go up on the overpass together, and Justice would watch Juanita get drunk and Juanita had learned enough by this time never to ask why Justice didn’t touch the alcohol or drugs or convenience store food, or was never even seen during the daytime. They sat together, and they would talk, and in the summer the desire was stifling. But Juanita never asked and so Justice never tasted her, never sipped from the magic fount that was her veins, though sometimes she went dizzy from the proximity of the perfume of her skin.<br>
<br>
There was nowhere to go after that. The memories fell down and on top of each other like little dominos, one triggering the other until all in a row the next wave came. Gently spurting blood on the swift brown hands, the involuntary tears slicking the cheeks and sparking the asthmatic breathing, the large pupils that seemed to cower in the sight of approaching death. The blood-stained hands clenching so tight, as if, with only gritted teeth and concentration, she could keep her soul in her body.<br>
<br>
“Yo sé que tu eres una bruja. Me ayudas…”<br>
<br>
Wordlessly, Justice had bit her wrist and held it out to Juanita. Immediately it turned violent. Juanita sucked the vitae so hard it felt as her capillaries were turning inside out—it had brought back the time twenty years before with a vengeance, lying in Kevin’s arms and feeling as if this fluid were the only thing that brought substance to the world, utter starmilk. Justice sank her teeth into Juanita’s neck and smeared her abdomen in the blood of Juanita’s torn stomach and sank into the ecstasy of the Kiss like the arms of a past lover. She could feel Juanita’s fluttering heartbeat in her flesh, becoming slower and steadier, and then deeper and darker, and then gone.<br>
<br>
Back to a threadbare apartment then: a true rat-hole, more like a nest than any haven in the true sense of the word. To watch the creamy skin turn pale and see her clench her hands and moan in sleep unnaturally deep. To awaken, finally, with a look gently dazed as if she had been dealt a stunning hit between the eyebrows. To see her eyes open and wordlessly ask the question with the muted expectation of horror in her gaze, oh god, what have you done to me?<br>
<br>
“Juanita, mi amor. Usted es un vampiro.”<br>
