<br>
Tired and hungry from battling the onslaught of her memories, Justice’s eyes are plastered open only by grim determination as she took the I-8 ramp from Highway 5. Her conversation with Kevin from a nightfall ago is still fresh in her mind—its innuendo and assumptions.<br>
<br>
Perhaps McGovern hasn’t realized that the only sensible place for her to go is San Diego. She can’t blame him for that, knowing his characteristic inability to remove his head from his ass. But she certainly isn’t about to enlighten the son of a bitch. The Marquis of San Diego is expecting her—and that is quite enough.<br>
<br>
The College Avenue exit presents itself with a flourish, as the lighted announcement board of the San Diego State Aztecs shows the pathway. It might seem deliberately of lower status, choosing to hold Court in the open square, just past the main entrance of the university, but anyone who is truly experienced with Anarchs should realize that this simply isn’t so. It is all about rebellion from oppression, and any way in which their message can be made known is gladly seized. A thumb in the eye of both the Sabbat and the Camarilla—call us children, please. Then you’ll be all the more surprised when we bite you.<br>
<br>
When she enters the square, it at first appears utterly deserted, the glass information dome of the Love Library glinting in the moonlight, the austere arrangements of stone benches and tree planters down the wide open stone corridor a tribute to order and discipline. But Justice knows well enough, from previous experience, that what actually rules here was an organized kind of unruliness, the most dangerous kind of all. Of course they have a sentry. He just hasn’t deigned to show himself yet.<br>
<br>
Then she notices the man in the dark trench coat leaning against the lamppost, smoking a cigarette.<br>
<br>
“You’re not blind.” He comments, as she approaches.<br>
<br>
“Not as far as vision goes.”<br>
<br>
“Excuse me the presumption, then. I was expecting someone far more dramatic.”<br>
<br>
“Who are you?”<br>
<br>
“Theodore Kazinsky, my dear dead lady. The town crier.”<br>
Despite the name, the vampire before her does not, at first glance, appear unkempt. His hair is short, dark and curly, a few strands escaping an old-fashioned fedora. His stature and presentation is clean-cut. The style is 1920’s, as is the crisp language. Perhaps he is indeed, or was once, Russian in origin—the figure is imposing without any directly noticeable attempt at being so, and his skin is on the whiter side of pale. “What exactly do you cry about?”<br>
<br>
“Everything.” The fedora is tilted back, and she can see his eyes in the lamplight, a darkly lined severe gray. Bloody tears cascade horrifyingly down his cheeks. She is breath-taken for a few moments before she realizes they are tattoos.<br>
<br>
“Perhaps not blind. But ignorant, she might be.”<br>
<br>
Quick to recover, she replies: “It’s a quality most people don’t usually recognize at first glance.”<br>
<br>
Kazinsky smiles, in a way that makes Justice sure that he has recognized all the possible responses to her previous comment and proclaimed them all legitimate. It is a smile of mild superiority, minced with a dash of satisfaction, and she recognizes it well.<br>
<br>
A good way to enter a city, pleasing the Herald, even if her intention is to leave, and soon.<br>
<br>
“Court will convene in about an hour. Have you established a Haven?”<br>
<br>
Justice nods, but Kazinsky must have caught the insecurity in the gesture, because he hands her a business card.<br>
<br>
“I suggest you travel here. The nightlife is a little noisy, but I’m certain you’re used to worse. The postal service is a little inefficient, but I promise no mad bombers will scatter your slumber. Get a little refreshment and return—we won’t scamper off without you.”<br>
<br>
Justice moistens her lips nervously. “Thank you.”<br>
<br>
“Don’t you worry about a thing, dear. Say hello to Chlöe for me—if it turns out to be one of her good days, that is.”<br>
<br>
The sound of his laughter follows her to her motorcycle, blending with the dangerous night.<br>
