<br>
Like everything else in this town, the apartment building smells of cigarettes.<br>
<br>
Just in case she has estimated the personalities of the residents incorrectly, Justice cuts the engine and coasts the last block or so to the residence, even though there are no stirs visible from without that are indicative of the feelings of those therein. A little of the mystery is cleared up when she enters the romanesque parlor on the first floor—the small office has been smashed to pieces, and the glass doors and faux wood paneling have all been scratched almost beyond recognition. Justice feels a bit of self-confidence start to return: it appears that she has not estimated them wrongly at all. Perhaps everything will go just as planned.<br>
<br>
But then, any seer could tell you that this is a bad time, and place, to take an omen.<br>
<br>
She finds the elevator in much the same condition as the office, so she climbs the carpeted stairwell that smells of chlorine with caution, looking for anyone with an ounce of authority that might be able to point out the ropes to her here. It is not until she nears the eighth floor that she hears what might be the sounds of weeping, and it is not until she tops it that she sees the girl. Crying gently and holding a menthol cigarette.<br>
<br>
Tears and Cigarettes. As good a summarization as any for this mini-world, Justice supposes.<br>
<br>
“What’s the matter?” Justice asks the girl, and the girl, upon hearing the voice, starts—as if she’d prefer to jump in shock but has forgotten how.<br>
<br>
“Not a thing.” The girl replies nervously, in a voice slow, thin, tiny and not at all beautiful. It’s a beaten puppy of a voice, but then so is her visage. She wears a sleeveless, short, black wool dress that looks like a mockery of her pale, emaciated frame. Her nails are bitten, and her glances are darting. After looking quickly from Justice to the floor three times in succession, she takes a long drag from the menthol and holds it in while she seems to gather her strength. “Why do people always think that something has to be wrong for you to be crying? It doesn’t. It absolutely doesn’t. I think it’s just the silliest thing in the world. Sometimes things are sad, so I cry for them. Sometimes they are happy, so I smile for them. But they are never wrong.”<br>
<br>
Justice has an inspiration. “Are you Chlöe?”<br>
<br>
“Of course. And you’re Justice, because you know me.” Something must have struck Chlöe as funny in that statement, because she erupts in peals of giggles with the tear tracks still fresh down her cheeks.<br>
<br>
“I’m Justice. I’m not sure I know you. Maybe I know of you, though.” Somehow, Justice does not want to engage in her customary handshake with this strange creature.<br>
<br>
The girl’s gaze all of a sudden becomes hooded and wary. “Maybe you do.” Chlöe then takes a last, quick drag and snuffs out her cigarette on the carpet. “At least that’s what Theodore said when he spoke inside my head.” As fast as it had come, the guarded fear was gone, leaving in its place an expression of iron-clad neutrality. “Well, come. You’ll want a house before you go and meet the king.”<br>
<br>
“Do you live in this building as well?” Justice asks as they enter the fire exit and turn down the tiled hallway. The halls, like the lobby downstairs, continue the 80’s roman theme with mirrored walls and brass sconces.<br>
<br>
“Oh yes. Up on the top, where there are no nasty hallways. I hate hallways.”<br>
<br>
It is easy to see why. All along the mirrored hall, Chlöe casts no reflection.<br>
<br>
“Here you go.” The girl finally says, halting at one point in the hallway and backpedaling to an apparently random doorway. “I think Mrs. Berkowitz used to live here, but maybe she’s dead now. In any case, she’s not here. So if you burn the tea cozies, it’ll feel just like home.” With a ferocious kick that Justice is surprised to see from those scrawny legs, Chlöe kicks in the door and grins in a satisfied way. She turns smartly, and leaves Justice to her own private orientation.<br>
<br>
“Bon appétit, or something like that.”<br>
