<br>
Justice cuts the engine on her motorcycle early and coasts into the parking lot that hides behind the bookstore at SDSU, sheltered by draping willows. The foliage muffles any sound that remains, hopefully. She does not wish to interrupt the already-progressing populace meeting more than is absolutely necessary. Anarchs can bite more viciously at times than the Camarilla, and might do so if one of the few traditions they respect is interrupted. In any case, Justice remembers the Marquis as being quick to punishment of all sorts: it would do well not to get on anyone’s bad side, not now, not when bad memories might still ache.<br>
<br>
She creeps into the back row of attending Kindred that are listening to the Marquis’ words. Public-service announcements from various quarters: Killings, apparently by members of the Sabbat, via raids from a stronghold in Mexico City. A bloodmobile, whose license has in the past been traced to Hunter activity, has been noticed during the day outside establishments that Kindred frequent, come nightfall. Report any unusual findings. Justice is glad she frequents the back row, where maybe the clueless look on her face isn’t evident to many of those around her. It used to be her practice during Populace in Santa Carla, as well, before in an acceptance born of desperation, she was made Primogen of her clan…<br>
<br>
A familiar voice rings out over the crowd. Justice is startled from her thoughts by it, and recognizes the Town Crier, assembled at the front, with the rest of the House of Lords. “We have a new attendee joining us tonight. Or perhaps I should say a new courtier, a new member of court, bereft of land or title.” Perhaps his voice is more mellifluous than it ought to be, carries better to every corner of the audience. “Justice always seems to come to us in times of trouble.” Snickers from the Lords.<br>
<br>
There are a few of the assembled that she recognizes, but more that she does not. Less than five years—barely a blink to the Camarilla, a time period over which very few Primogen would fall, even the stupid or innocent. But an Anarch government, obviously, has a faster turn-around time. Most of the Lords don’t give notice to her scrutiny, but something in the flick of Theodore’s dark eyes makes her think he does, and more so: almost makes her think he can trace her thoughts. But he says nothing. “Would you please step forward, and present yourself to the Marquis?”<br>
<br>
The crowd parts nervously for Justice, to the side and behind her, leaving her alone in front of the dozen deadly individuals. The Marquis looks down at where she is kneeling, and over the years, he has not been replaced. An imposing man, dark and austere looking, the black coat edged with silver. Regal in the fashion that Prince Mordred must have been, the dark coin of his father, at King Arthur’s court. Stern, though, and unaffected.<br>
<br>
“From what House do you hail?” The Marquis’ voice is level, but deep. It dredges out the solemnity from any gathered, speaks to the dark places in the quiet night. Justice clears her throat nervously, buying herself time to try and remember the codes, the pseudonyms, from the last time she had to use them. Precious seconds before relief floods over her. “The…the warrior-poets, my liege.” She says, as she remembers.<br>
<br>
“Justice, then, of the Warrior-Poets.” And then, the words no new member of a city ever wants to hear. “I remember you.” Justice swears she can hear the rustlings of clothing as the gathered populace leans in to hear better. “As you should recall, any gathered in this domain that number more than three are represented in the House of Lords. You bow to Callas, who bows to me. Requests of me from you go through Callas.” He gestures, and one of the Lords that Justice vaguely recognized inclines his head. “I trust you understand the edicts of this domain?”<br>
<br>
“Yes, my Lord.” Justice’s heart, if it still could, would be hammering in her chest, awaiting the question she is certain is coming. The silence is alive, for her, with apprehension.<br>
<br>
“I’m…equally certain, that you remember the circumstances under which you last took leave of us.”<br>
<br>
“Yes, my Lord.” A mad desire floods her to attempt to babble an explanation, just so she no longer has to feel her his gaze on the back of her bowed head, but she bites her tongue.<br>
<br>
“You bring no other problems to our shores this time, I hope?” The words wry, slightly biting. “No other childer to wreck certain havoc?”<br>
<br>
Not yet, Justice thinks. The image flashes in her mind, of curious, shiny eyes. Marisa sucking on a juicebox of blood back at the apartment. Hopefully Chlöe does not check the closets when she is not present at populace. “No, my Lord.” She swallows her pride. “I beg your apology for the incident of years past, my Lord. It was never my intention. Juanita betrayed me as surely as she betrayed you.” A silence of the crowd, as she considers her next words, is deep. “Should I find her in this domain, is her life forfeit?”<br>
<br>
        Rustlings among the House of Lords. Callas speaks up. “Sabbat have no recognition here. We would ask that you put her execution in our hands, so we can make sure it done correctly, or it might reflect even worse upon yourself.”<br>
<br>
        Shame joins with apprehension and creates an emotional vice. “Yes, my Liege.”<br>
<br>
        The Marquis speaks up again. “That is all.” He gestures toward her, and Justice is versed enough to step back into the relative safety of the crowd, the curious glances burning holes of guilt in her armor of idealism. Theodore speaks up again.<br>
<br>
        “Do any others crave recognition from the Marquis?” Silence, waiting. No one steps forward.<br>
<br>
        “Then good night.” The Town Crier says. Justice looks towards the front, and swears that he is looking directly at her as his mouth forms the next words. Chills run down her back. “And good Hunting.” He tips his fedora to the crowd, his gaze never deviating from her own horrified one, and the crowd bleeds away.<br>
