<br>
All of a sudden, Justice was able to read his lips and realized what he was saying.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ayudas. Ayudas. Por favor, me Ayudas. Por favor dios, Santo Maria, excepto mí.”<br>
<br>
Shit. Juanita was looking quietly horrified. Justice moved beside her and put a hand on her shoulder.<br>
<br>
“The Kiss takes away all pain, Juanita. You can help him. You’ll only take a little, and then he’ll be on the street again, and remembering nothing.”<br>
<br>
Juanita’s gaze turned to Justice’s face, and it appeared shattered, hopelessly distant, almost lost. Good at least that she didn’t know the lie present in the words. Brujah weren’t Ventrue, they couldn’t make their victims forget. He would probably suffer the rest of his days with memories of this night. And Baby Brujah, Baby Vampires in general—the first feeding was before they learned self-control. Almost always, the supplier of the first feeding died.<br>
<br>
But it didn’t turn out that way this time. Maybe it was due to the extreme closeness that had shared even before Juanita had become a vampire, maybe she had let something slip in the words, but Juanita turned towards Justice and sized her up instantly. “You’re lying. I don’t know about what, but you are.”<br>
<br>
Justice’s heart sank. “Juanita…”<br>
<br>
“And it hurts me, too. How can you be such monsters, to think only about his pain? Oh, his pain is the easy one, he is the one straining under the ropes and bleeding there and crying for God to save him, as I did once. I got Satan in return, witchcraft, and is that to be his release now? How could I do it? How?”<br>
<br>
Justice lead Juanita over to the drooping couch and sat her down, mindless entirely of the young man still tied in the middle of the living room. “Juanita, I understand, I really do. But if you don’t drink, you’ll die, and in excruciating pain. You can’t eat normal food anymore. Blood is everything.”<br>
<br>
Juanita began sobbing bitterly. Justice touched the thick hair, mahogany midnight, almost a pelt, lightly. Her intention was entirely to comfort—she never could have imagined that Juanita would object to feeding. In her line of work, protecting the chola or its acquisitions, people had died regularly, and she hadn’t seemed to mind killing them.<br>
<br>
“Don’t touch me.” A delayed reaction, because Juanita had allowed it for the first few moments. What poisonous thoughts were circling in her brain, to keep her from everything Justice knew she wanted and needed? “I know the blood is everything. You turned me with blood, you changed me with it, into a monster, like you. A vampire, you said. A vampire. A demon that sucks on the souls of others in order to prolong its unnatural life. I didn’t know. God, I didn’t know. And if I had, I would gladly have died.”<br>
<br>
Justice was at a loss for words. She had embraced Juanita in a moment of sheer love and pity. How do you feel when the receiver of the transplanted organ tells you she’d like to toss that damn kidney right back in your face? And Justice couldn’t bring herself to take Juanita’s delicate wrists and force her to the ground, to let the smell of the vitae get into her nose until it was overwhelming. She supposed this was why you were never supposed to embrace someone you loved. Vampirism is a cold, unfeeling, business. But in the end, why do you bring someone into the fold? Loneliness, nine times out of ten. Vampirism makes eternity cold and unfeeling, but that doesn’t mean you ever stop hoping it won’t be.<br>
<br>
As if to emphasize that statement, Kevin came in, then, from the lone bedroom. His gray eyes flickered over the restrained young man, and Justice and Juanita aptly not-commiserating on the couch. He didn’t need to ask what was wrong. He sighed, as if this all bored and pained him on some very shallow level. “Juanita.” He said, the tones dulcet and compelling. Had he used that voice on Justice, she knew she would have been all over him in a minute. But Juanita apparently had greater powers of self-control.<br>
<br>
“No.” Juanita spit out the words bitterly. “I won’t do it. Kill me, or let me die.”<br>
<br>
“Juanita.” Came the tones again, sweet to the ear, sweet to the mind, convincing. “I’m not asking you to touch him. Pretend he isn’t there. Just come to me.”<br>
<br>
Juanita hesitated, halfway, Justice could tell, between walking over to him like it was no big deal and what the hell was his problem, or refusing for the sheer deviant pleasure of making him mad. Well, once Juanita had known him a little longer, she would see. You couldn’t make Kevin mad. He was utterly unaffected. In the worst of cases, he would remove himself from your presence before he was tempted to drop his shield of austerity and rush you, teaching you the hard way.<br>
<br>
“No.” Juanita finally decided, and the word sounded in very inflection like a stubborn two-year old.<br>
<br>
“Juanita.” Came a third time, slightly chastising, as if he was questioning, inside, why exactly he had to do even this, light scolding though it was. A shaming that was gentle, even, as if it was a social impasse in this room with just the three—four—of them. She shouldn’t need this convincing. She should know what was good for her. He doesn’t want to hurt her. She should go to him…now. Holding her breath, Justice watched as Juanita bit back a compulsive shudder and walked over to Kevin, like a striding panther.<br>
<br>
“Okay. What the hell do you want?” Juanita asked, studying his bare feet in the somehow-elegant striped bathrobe. Across the room, Justice managed to tear her glance from Kevin’s face to his feet, as well. They flexed on the carpet, bared the tendons straight, curled and uncurled, stretching as though they were preparing to run, to sprint, to chase down. Had it not been wildly inappropriate, Justice might have giggled. She and Juanita were both staring in fascination at Kevin’s creepy feet. But the Beast inside her knew what it meant. Whether or not he showed it, Kevin had considerable emotion invested in this situation. Something about the here and now was important to him, and his willingness to use his physical strength, rather than his far-greater social, said something.<br>
<br>
“I don’t want anything. Just stand here with me.” Twilight, dusky and enveloping, that voice.<br>
<br>
Justice bit her lip as Kevin laid a hand on Juanita’s shoulder. Juanita breathed out, slow and deep, her self-control on the edge of firmly in place, trying so desperately to look dignified. The wrong move now could be disastrous, in the form of the slightest humiliation on Juanita’s part sending her stalking out of the apartment, to find some way to prove her power and her strength. And what, Justice worried hopelessly at the thought like a dog without teeth at a tough bone, if the Thirst should hit her then?<br>
<br>
“That’s it.” Kevin said encouragingly, as Juanita hadn’t moved. “Now. Sit with me, Juanita. Right here, yes, on the floor. That’s just fine.” Kevin’s hands moved from Juanita’s shoulder to hold her hands, the both of them in a way that seemed gentle, but could turn to a hold she couldn’t escape from more quickly than a breath. “Just relax.” His one hand holding both of hers, his free hand touched her eyelashes, smoothing them down. “Calm down.”<br>
<br>
The wrong words. One eye flashed open. “I am calm.” Kevin expertly regained control of the situation.<br>
<br>
“Of course you are. You’re just so tense. It’s fine. Don’t worry about anything. We’ll take care of everything.” The hand moving back to her shoulders, the thumb relaxing the seizing knots out of her corded neck.<br>
<br>
“I can’t drink from him. I can’t do that.” The breath coming like it did before the bloody tears started, biting her lip to try and stop them, and Juanita, somehow, in some totally unexpected way, able to tell her emotional problems to Kevin instead of to Justice, who at one point, Justice was certain, she had loved. What was it about the son of a bitch, that he could come in with a strength that was wrapped in silk and totally disarm you so that you felt like you were drowning in all the good emotions?<br>
<br>
“I know. Shhh, shhh. Don’t worry about it. Just sit for a minute, and relax.” And Juanita relaxed, no longer having to bite her lip, breathing gently, almost fluidly. No bitter tears of rage and self-hate. Calm and very obviously trying to get a grip, to please Kevin, if nothing else. That tension that could be labeled as nothing but the smallest amount of jealousy flooded through Justice. Her childer, and Kevin was taking control, just as he always did. Damn him. Even if he was doing what he asked her to do, even if this worked out beautifully, good cop and bad cop, damn him.<br>
<br>
“Now, Juanita. I want you to look me in the eye.” Kevin said, slowly and inexorably. Juanita resisted moving from her place of peace for a moment, skin around the eyes tightening in stress and pain, and slight anger. But she didn’t want to show any of that to Kevin, smooth-talking charming Southern asshole that he was, and so she relaxed again, calmed herself down, and opened her eyes, slowly, to stare directly in Kevin’s own. Eyes of the darkest chocolate, full of emotion, rage and pain and passion, pitted again eyes of lightest gray ice, full of…nothing. Absolutely nothing.<br>
<br>
“Juanita. Bite him.”<br>
<br>
Could angels have seen, or cared to see, they would have wept at the sight of Juanita falling to Kevin McGovern’s domination, and falling upon the restrained young man with relish and hunger. They would have cried diamond tears to see her give in to her Beast, her thirst unrestrained, gulping down the sticky red mortality with all the passion that she had originally used to resist it. It was a lion clawing apart a wildebeest with complete and utter abandon, the monster released, a true rape of purity in it’s deepest sense. It was a shame, and the ultimate sorrow, but it was Juanita’s first triumph, though unwilling, over the night.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bscbnforum58570.showUserPublicProfile?gid=stephencrowley>Stephen Crowley</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 126<br> <font color=#FF9300>(2/2/03 8:01:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=65.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Foreshadowing a blazing... = Justice</span><hr size=1> Twilight, now, and ever darker.<br>
<br>
Disposing of a human body was a nasty business: dangerous and tiring through its required extremely high attention to detail. Thus, Kevin had been up long into the night, after Juanita had collapsed in the bedroom in utter sated exhaustion, though weeping bitter tears.<br>
<br>
Justice had helped where she could. She had removed the skin of the hands, feet and face, soaked them in ether for a few hours to heighten flammability and disguise the distinctly identifiable odor of burning human flesh, and stuck them in the furnace of the apartment complex, waiting until they were consumed to ash. Kevin had done the messy work, though, and Justice had never seen him more gently apologetic then she had in that instance, in the uncomplaining silence with which he went about his portion. Placing the body on a plastic sheet, he had set to it with a truncheon and a splintering baseball bat, and by the time they both were done, Juanita’s first meal looked enough like a gang ambush to withstand police medical inspection. Then he had bundled the body in brown paper, easy to dispose of, and kept nasty stains off the car, and driven it the short, nerve-wracking distance to the local marsh.<br>
<br>
“You could have a place here, you and her both. If you don’t fuck it up. I don’t have any reason to stay here if I’m caught.” He had said as explanation for his uncharacteristically generous acts. Justice had nodded, suspecting him still—after all, when had he ever cared about her welfare?—seen him off, and gone to sleep on the living-room couch. When she woke, at the darker side of dusk, Juanita was nowhere to be found in the apartment and Kevin had either commandeered the bed, or shared it. It couldn’t be known, and it couldn’t be cared about. In any case, Juanita would always do whatever she damn well pleased. But Justice had an idea where she might have gone, her childe, so resistant to the dictates and prices of immortality.<br>
<br>
She scaled the overpass as easily as she had a few weeks ago: Juanita had lately been reluctant to go outdoors at all, though for what reasons she did not reveal. Given her outbursts last night, she might think that the outdoors were not allowed for monsters, or she might have thought of them for once, and been worried about running into her old chola. Justice considered the latter of these two the more unlikely option, however. When had Juanita ever given a care for them? Words appeared in her brain to mock her, and they had Juanita’s characteristic, musical Spanish accent—‘a monster may as well embrace the night completely.’<br>
<br>
She was there, and made no move to acknowledge or deny Justice’s presence in any way. She was completely absorbed in a game of basketball, going on in a makeshift court set up close to the railway yard. Every once in awhile fights broke out, though these were settled more through posturing than fists. These players had enough violence in their everyday lives of street survival that games called for no more. It was possible that Juanita had gone out here to watch and hear the game with her unnaturally keen senses. It was more probable that she had come here to be able to mock Justice, when she came to collect her.<br>
<br>
Justice sat a few feet from Juanita, and waited a few seconds before saying the scripted sentence. “You’re not one of them, anymore.”<br>
<br>
Juanita, ever quick on the uptake, replied, “And whose fault is that?” Though in this barbed, blaming statement, she doesn’t turn to look her sire in the eye. From that alone, Justice can garner a little hope.<br>
<br>
“Both of ours, if any. But look. You can’t keep torturing yourself.” She bit her lip before saying the dreaded words that had to come. “Sooner or later, you’ll have to decide.”<br>
<br>
“Decide what?” Juanita asked, feigning innocence. “There’s no decision to be made, ai? It’s been done.” Silence for a minute. “I’m adjusting. You said I’d need time to adjust, like some fucking city shrink, and that’s what I’m fucking doing. So leave me the hell alone.”<br>
<br>
“All right.” Justice stood, and brushed imaginary dust from her jeans. “Kevin and I are going out, later, once the bars are full. If you want to come, you’re welcome.”<br>
<br>
Juanita was still sulky. “I don’t have an ID.”<br>
<br>
“With Kevin, that won’t be a problem.”<br>
<br>
This time, the voice definitely had a grudge in it, though it wasn’t dipped in poison, like some of her words of late had been. More resentful, Justice decided, of having to make known the fact that she actually cared. “Can you do things like that? Make…people…do things?” The tension was clearly evident in her body when she said the words.<br>
<br>
“Not like Kevin did last night.” Good cop, bad cop! her brain screamed. Don’t switch sides! She needs to live somehow, and if she won’t learn from you, and you convince her not to learn from Kevin… “Each clan has different powers.” She said, squashing the voice down into the deepest recesses of her conscience. “Naturally, by the power of our blood, we can move quickly, have lots of strength, and can be…extremely charming. What Kevin did, or at least how it seemed to me, was the hallmark of a different clan, the ones that usually rule our kind. Making people do what you command them to—you can imagine it might come in handy.”<br>
<br>
“Rule?” The word was scoffing. “You have immortality, and use it for fucking power games? Proletariat and Bourgeoisie, is that how it is? Some elite upper class, of mummies, maybe? Dead people that used to be kings?”<br>
<br>
“The Princes will tell you that power is everything. And when you have so many of our kind under your control, you can get a good many things done. For good or for evil is your choice in the matter.”<br>
<br>
“Yeah, well, being extremely charming—what the hell is that? How can that get you anywhere? Strong and fast, I can see. Strong to get you things, and fast to get out of there when you…get something that wasn’t what you wanted. But what about the other? You bat your eyelashes and they give you the world on a silver platter?”<br>
<br>
“Don’t sell it short.” Justice warned. “As you saw with Kevin, you can learn other powers, if you have someone to teach you. And I’ve seen elders of our kind calm an entire crowd or incite them to riot. Kevin can call to him anyone he’s ever met, across the world, simply by letting it be known that he wants them, and they cannot resist. There are possibilities to it.”<br>
<br>
“Maybe.” Juanita said, and for the first time in days, her voice did not sound quite as black as once it had. “Maybe.”<br>
<br>
“So stick with it. Wait and see.” And with that, Justice turned to really go. She had some questions she wanted to ask Kevin about the previous night.<br>
<br>
“What was the decision you were talking about?” Juanita wanted to ask, as a parting question. “You’re acting as if there’s some other choice than immortality.”<br>
<br>
Justice had answered, “Well, there’s sunlight. Sunlight and fire, both of them kill us. So there’s always a way out if you really can’t take it.”<br>
<br>
Looking back on it now, it seemed possible that giving Juanita that particular piece of information might have been a big mistake.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm19.showPrevMessage?topicID=65.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm19.showNextMessage?topicID=65.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=65.topic&index=6><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/prefabs/ez/addreply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"><a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm19.threadControl?topicID=65.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/posticons/techops.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm19.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=65.topic>Subscribe</a> Click to receive email notification of replies<br>  <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm19.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=65.topic>Unsubscribe</a> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies<br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="right"><td colspan=2><form action=http://pub98.ezboard.com/BBSForum.jumpShowForum method=post><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="1"><tr><td><b>jump to:</b><select name=forumName><option value="scbnforum58570frm12">Blackjack's Message Board <option value="scbnforum58570frm21">The Barrens<option value="scbnforum58570frm23">Domain Status<option value="scbnforum58570frm18">The Santa Carla Tribune<option value="scbnforum58570frm19">Literary<option value="scbnforum58570frm16">Players Forum<option value="scbnforum58570frm17">Storyteller and Narrator Announcements